In addition, since 75% of India's electricity is produced by CPPs, the following components of cycling costs for CPPs must be considered before concluding on the grid-parity of RE (CEA, 2017b):

                              •

Increase in maintenance, operation (excluding fixed costs), and capital overhaul expenditures;


                              •

Cost of start-up fuel, auxiliary power, chemicals, and extra manpower for start-ups;


                              •

Cost of Short-Term Efficiency loss;


                              •

Cost of heat rate changes due to low load and variable load operation;


                              •

Cost of long-term heat-rate increases (a part of which is not restored even after overhauling);


                              •

Long-term generation capacity cost increases due to the shortening of plant equipment life;


                              •

Cost of replacement power due to the increased forced outage.
